.TH "urr" "1" "2026-04-12" "December 2025" "Wake-on-LAN Utility"
.PP
.SH NAME
.PP
urr - A lightweight Wake-on-LAN tool with hostname resolution
.PP
.SH SYNOPSIS
.PP
\fB\fRurr\fB\fR [\fB-f\fR \fIFILE\fR] [\fITARGET\fR]
\fB\fRurr\fB\fR [\fB-h\fR | \fB--help\fR]
\fB\fRurr\fB\fR [\fB-v\fR | \fB--version\fR]
.PP
.SH DESCRIPTION
.PP
\fB\fRurr\fB\fR sends a "Magic Packet" to a target network card to wake a computer over
the network.\& The program first checks if the \fBTARGET\fR is a valid MAC address.\&
If it is not, it attempts to resolve the \fBTARGET\fR as a hostname by looking it
up in a configuration file.\&
Urr is imperative: "wake up!\&" in Hebrew.\&
.PP
.SH OPTIONS
.PP
\fB\fR-f\fB\fR, \fB\fR--file\fB\fR \fIFILE\fR
.RS 4
Use \fIFILE\fR as the hosts database instead of the default.\&
.PP
.RE
\fB\fR-h\fB\fR, \fB\fR--help\fB\fR
.RS 4
Show the help message and exit.\&
.PP
.RE
\fB\fR-v\fB\fR, \fB\fR--version\fB\fR
.RS 4
Show program version and license information.\&
.PP
.RE
.SH FILES
.PP
\fB\(ti/.\&config/urr/hosts\fR
.RS 4
The default database file.\& The format is "mac-address hostname" per line,
matching the /etc/ethers(5) format.\&
Lines starting with '\&#'\& are ignored.\&
.PP
.RE
\fB/usr/local/share/urr/examples/hosts\fR
.RS 4
A template file provided during installation.\&
.PP
.RE
.SH EXAMPLES
.PP
\fB\fRurr 00:11:22:33:44:55\fB\fR
.RS 4
Send a magic packet to a specific MAC address.\&
.PP
.RE
\fB\fRurr nas\fB\fR
.RS 4
Lookup the MAC address for '\&nas'\& in the default hosts file and wake it.\&
.PP
.RE
\fB\fRurr -f .\&/my_hosts office-pc\fB\fR
.RS 4
Use a local file to resolve '\&office-pc'\&.\&
.PP
.RE
